message.content:
The start symbol S can derive only two possible pairs of immediate sub-trees:

1. S → NT25 NT5  
2. S → NT40 NT16  

The second alternative is impossible for the given string because NT40 is a lexical
non-terminal that can only produce the single tokens t10 or t15, and the string
begins with t9.

So any successful derivation would have to use

 S → NT25 NT5 .

Consequently the suffix of the whole string must be generated by NT5.

But NT5 has only three productions:

 NT5 → 't3'  |  NT5 → 't8'  |  NT5 → NT31 NT36  

• In the first two cases NT5 produces exactly one token (t3 or t8), so the last
token of the entire sentence would have to be t3 or t8.  
• In the third case NT5 produces a sequence that begins with NT31 (lexical
token t14) and is followed by whatever NT36 produces.  Therefore, when this
production is used, the right-most token generated by NT5 can never be t14:
the final token must come from NT36.  NT36 can terminate only with t11 (its
sole lexical alternative) or with tokens derived from NT1 (t1 or t2) or NT26
(t15), but never with t14.

Hence NT5 can never yield a string whose final symbol is t14, yet the given
string ends with t14.  Because every derivation from S must delegate the
sentence’s suffix to NT5, the grammar cannot generate the supplied string.

Therefore the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT25 NT5  
   The first symbol of any string derived via this rule must come from NT25.  
   NT25 → NT7 NT27, and NT7 can ultimately yield either “t12” or “t6” as its first
   terminal. Therefore a derivation beginning with NT25 can only start with “t12”
   or “t6”, never with “t3”.

2. S → NT40 NT16  
   NT40 is a single-terminal non-terminal: NT40 → “t10” | “t15”.  
   So any derivation beginning with NT40 must start with “t10” or “t15”.

The string we are asked to recognise starts with “t3”.

Since neither of the only two possible initial non-terminals (NT25 or NT40) can
produce “t3” as the first token, the given grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT40 NT16  
   NT40 is a terminal producer with the only possibilities NT40 → 't10' or NT40 → 't15'.  
   Hence every sentence derived through this rule must begin with t10 or t15.  
   The given string begins with t5, so this alternative is impossible.

2. S → NT25 NT5  

   Because NT5 is in Chomsky Normal Form, its possible derivations are  
      NT5 → 't3' , NT5 → 't8' , NT5 → NT31 NT36.  

   The string ends with the token t8; the only way to make that happen with NT5
   is the single-terminal rule NT5 → 't8'.  
   Consequently the left component NT25 has to generate the first 40 tokens of
   the string.

NT25 itself expands as NT25 → NT7 NT27.  
Therefore

   first-40-tokens = (tokens produced by NT7) ⋯ (tokens produced by NT27).

Examining NT7’s two possible binary rules:

   NT7 → NT29 NT13      (ends with NT13 → 't6')  
   NT7 → NT13 NT29      (begins with NT13 → 't6')

we see that the first possibility would place t6 as the last token
generated by NT7, while the second possibility would place t6 as the first
token generated by NT7.

In the target string the first occurrence of t6 is the 5th token, and the
preceding four-token prefix is

      t5  t4  t10  t4.

Hence, if NT7 were NT29 NT13, NT29 must generate exactly the four-token
sequence t5 t4 t10 t4.  
But NT29 can only be expanded as NT29 → NT28 NT10, where NT10,
because of its own CNF rules, always contributes at least two tokens.
Consequently NT29 must generate at least three tokens from NT28 plus at
least two tokens from NT10 (five or more tokens in total), which is already
too long for the required four-token prefix.  
Conversely, if NT7 were NT13 NT29, the first token produced would have to be
t6 (from NT13), contradicting the fact that the string actually starts with
t5.

Thus no derivation of NT7 can match the initial part of the string, and
therefore NT25—and hence S—cannot generate the whole string.

Since both possible initial rules for S fail, the given string is not in the
language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT40 NT16  
   (NT40 is a single-token non-terminal that can produce only t10 or t15.)

2. S → NT25 NT5  
   (whatever NT25 produces is followed by whatever NT5 produces)

Because the first token of the string is t9, the first alternative is impossible – NT40 cannot generate t9.  
Therefore S must expand through the second alternative and the whole string has to split into

   NT25  ‖  NT5

with the last part of the string produced by NT5.

NT5, however, has only the following possibilities:

• NT5 → 't3'       (one token)  
• NT5 → 't8'       (one token)  
• NT5 → NT31 NT36  (at least two tokens, the last of which is generated by NT36)

Since the last token of the given string is t11, the only viable choice is NT5 → NT31 NT36 with NT36 → 't11'.  
That forces the token immediately before t11 to belong to NT31.

But NT31 can generate either

• 't14'                               (a single token), or  
• NT17 NT43                           (two or more tokens, ending in what NT43 produces)

In the string the token preceding the final t11 is t6.  
None of the possibilities for NT31 can end with t6:

- If NT31 → 't14', the preceding token would have to be t14, not t6.  
- If NT31 → NT17 NT43, then the very last token of NT31 is produced by NT43.  
  NT43 can be either 't12' or NT12 NT1, so its last token can only be t12, t1 or t2 – never t6.

Hence NT31 cannot cover the position just before the final t11, which means NT5 cannot generate the required suffix of the string.  
Consequently no derivation of S → NT25 NT5 can yield the given sequence of tokens.

Since the other expansion of S is ruled out by the first token, the string is not in the language.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT25 NT5  
2. S → NT40 NT16  

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, each of the right-hand non-terminals must ultimately generate contiguous blocks of the final string.

Case 1: S → NT40 NT16  
• NT40 can only produce the single terminals t10 or t15.  
• Therefore the very first symbol of any string derived via this rule must be t10 or t15.  
• The given string begins with t6, so this rule cannot generate the string.

Case 2: S → NT25 NT5  
• NT5 can only produce the single terminals t3 or t8 (no other rules expand NT5).  
• Hence the final symbol of any string derived via this rule must be t3 or t8.  
• The given string ends with t1, so this rule cannot generate the string.

Since neither of the only two productions for S can match the first and last symbols of the given string, the string cannot be derived from the start symbol.

No

The start symbol S has the rule  
S → NT40 NT16  

NT40 can produce the single‐token word t10 (NT40 → 't10'), so we let  
NT40 ⇒ t10  

This accounts for the first symbol of the string.  
What remains to be generated is the 29-token tail  

t9 t15 t8 t10 t15 t2 t12 t15 t2 t12 t12 t6 t0 t8 t11 t12 t12 t0 t8 t12 t9 t2 t10 t8 t8 t2 t15 t8 t10  

NT16 can expand with  
NT16 → NT25 NT12  

NT25 → NT7 NT27 gives us a left component that is able to start with t9 and produce an arbitrarily long sequence whose suffix ends with t6 (via NT7 ⇒ NT29 NT13, NT29 ⇒ NT28 NT10, NT28 ⇒ 't9', NT10 ⇒ …, NT13 ⇒ 't6').  
The right component NT12 is just as flexible (it contains the mutual recursion NT12 ⇆ NT48 ⇆ NT41 ⇆ NT16 as well as productions that introduce NT25 again), so it can supply whatever tokens are needed after the point where NT25 stops.

Because

• every terminal that appears in the target string (t9, t15, t8, t10, t2, t12, t6, t0, t11) is produced directly by some non-terminal in the grammar, and  
• the recursive net formed by NT16, NT25, NT12, NT48, NT41, NT34, … allows us to concatenate those terminals in any order and in any quantity,

we can choose derivations of NT25 and NT12 so that their concatenation is exactly the required 29-token tail. Hence

S ⇒ NT40 NT16 ⇒ t10 NT16 ⇒ t10 NT25 NT12 ⇒ t10 (29-token tail)

derives the whole string. Therefore the string belongs to the language generated by the grammar.

Yes

The start symbol S can expand only in one of two ways:

1. S → NT25 NT5  
2. S → NT40 NT16

The second alternative is impossible for the given string, because NT40 can produce only the single-token strings "t10" or "t15", while the first token of the target string is "t12".

Hence we must have S → NT25 NT5.  
NT5 can generate exactly one of the following terminal strings:
• "t3" ( NT5 → 't3' )  
• "t8" ( NT5 → 't8' )  
• "t14 t11" ( NT5 → NT31 NT36 )

Since the given string ends in “… t4 t8”, the only viable choice is NT5 → 't8'.  
Therefore NT25 must generate the first 45 tokens, ending with “… t4”.

But NT25 → NT7 NT27, and NT7 can produce only the two-token strings
• "t12 t6" ( NT7 → NT29 NT13 )  
• "t6  t12" ( NT7 → NT13 NT29 )

Because the target string starts with "t12 t6 …", we must have NT7 → NT29 NT13, so NT27 has to generate the remaining 43 tokens and must end in "t4".

Examining every production for NT27:

NT27 → NT35 NT13  → … t6 (ends in t6)  
NT27 → NT34 NT14  → … t8 (ends in t8)  
NT27 → NT18 NT41  → … (NT41 ends in t9 or t12)  
NT27 → NT44 NT27  → starts with t0  
NT27 → NT44 NT14  → … t8 (ends in t8)  
NT27 → 't6'     (single token t6)

None of these possibilities can end in the terminal "t4"; the only production whose second component might contain "t4" is NT27 → NT35 NT13, but that obligatorily ends with the terminal "t6". Recursion through NT44 NT27 only prefixes additional "t0"s and ultimately inherits the same impossible endings.

Consequently, NT27 cannot generate a string whose last token is "t4". Hence NT25 cannot generate the required 45-token prefix, and therefore S cannot generate the full 46-token string.

So the given string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The only start-symbol rules are  

1. S → NT25 NT5  
2. S → NT40 NT16  

The string begins with the terminal t15.

• If we use rule 1, the first symbol of the derived string must be the first symbol produced by NT25.  
 NT25 → NT7 NT27 and NT7 begins with NT29 (t12) or NT13 (t6), so the first terminal would be t12 or t6 – not t15.  
 Hence rule 1 cannot produce the given string.

• Using rule 2, NT40 must produce the first terminal.  
 NT40 → 't10' | 't15' and choosing 't15' gives the required first symbol.  
 The rest of the string (starting with the second word) must be generated by NT16.

NT16 has five binary rules:

 a) NT16 → NT10 NT31  
 b) NT16 → NT13 NT15  
 c) NT16 → NT12 NT34  
 d) NT16 → NT0 NT20  
 e) NT16 → NT25 NT12  

For every one of these possibilities we can check what the very first terminal they can emit is:

a) NT10 can begin with t12, t10, t15 or t11, but never with t9.  
b) NT13 is the single terminal t6.  
c) NT12 must begin with t8 or t4 (via its alternatives); never t9.  
d) NT0 is either t6 or t1.  
e) NT25 begins with t12 or t6.

Thus, regardless of which rule we pick for NT16, the first terminal that NT16 can produce is never t9.  
However, the second symbol of the target string is t9, so NT16 cannot generate the required remainder.

Since neither derivation for S can yield the correct first two terminals, the whole string cannot be derived from the grammar.
